songs.title: Let’s Save Tony Orlando’s House

description.plain:
This song was in part inspired by, and takes its title from an episode of The Simpsons entitled “Marge on the Lam.” In this episode actor Troy McClure introduces himself by saying  “You might remember me from such tele-thons as ‘Out with Gout '88’ and ‘Let’s Save Tony Orlando’s House.’”



In a Q&A Session, the band explain they use working titles for bits of jams they record to later work on. A specific series was named by James McNew after “Troy McClure’s voluminous [fictional] resumé”, such as “Astroheist Gemini”, “The Greatest Story Ever Hooled” and “Leper in the Back Field”. Yo La Tengo would eventually record a version of The Simpsons Theme Song clearly inspired by The Beatles' “Tomorrow Never Knows”.

The lyrics, written by Hubley based on McNeal’s working title, details a fictional account of Frankie Valli, of Four Seasons fame, taking revenge on crooner Tony Orlando.

songs.full_title: Deeper into Movies by Yo La Tengo
songs.title: Deeper into Movies

description.plain:
Deeper Into Movies was originally released on I Can Hear the Heart Beating as One and later re-recorded on Stuff Like That There.

There is marked contrast between the two versions of the song, in part, because of a lack of distortion in the guitars, but also due to the absence of a drum track.

According to Ira Kaplan, the decision to exclude drums was a bit of a happy accident.

“I said the record was more studio-y than we expected, and Georgia played drums and everything, but there are no drums on ‘Deeper into Movies’ because we took them off,” Kaplan told Salon. “She did play, but we did a lot of tinkering with that one. Just one day, faders went up when someone went to record — someone forgot to put the drum fader up and we just thought, ‘Wow, that sounds really good that way.’ Another thing I was trying to do conceptually was just play in standard tuning, and then I did a lot, but it ended up being a number song, like that one, with a weird tuning, and some other ones, I used a capo.”

songs.title: Tears Are in Your Eyes

description.plain:
“Tears Are In Your Eyes” is about a person’s perspective on someone close who is suffering from clinical depression. At a 2003 show, the band dedicated the song to Johnny Cash and June Carter who died within several months of each other in 2003.

“Tears Are In Your Eyes” was covered by The Antlers eight years later, with some minor lyrical changes. The cover was featured on their 3-song EP New York Hospitals, which was the predecessor to the concept album Hospice

The track was also covered by English singer-songwriter Adem, in 2008 and was featured on his third full-length.

The song title is a reference to Yo La Tengo’s appearance on the 1995 Lollapalooza tour.

The band performed mid-afternoon sets on the festival’s side stage. Often performing earlier in the afternoon was the artist Moby. One of the instruments that Moby used in his performance was the Roland Octapad, an electronic percussion instrument.



When taking the stage for their own performance, Yo La Tengo frequently noticed roadie’s tape with MOBY OCTAPAD written on it, still left on the stage after Moby’s set. The band later used this anecdote as the title for an instrumental that they were jamming on. Lyrics unrelated to the Moby story were added later.

songs.full_title: Tom Courtenay by Yo La Tengo
songs.title: Tom Courtenay

description.plain:
The title of this song is a reference to BAFTA-winning, stage and screen British actor Tom Courtenay, active since the 1960s.



The lyrics, however, do not mention Tom, only fellow British actresses Julie Christie and Eleanor Bron, as well as Paul McCartney.

A fan in SongMeanings shines a light on the lyrics as a whole:

Back on 2001 I was at a Yo La Tengo’s concert which was followed by a questions-and-answers session where the band sat at the stage and talked to those of us who stayed. I was quick to ask Ira Kaplan what was the meaning behind this song. He wasn’t very specific saying that it wasn’t about a particular event or person, but rather about all the things which allure you in cinema, literature and the media in general when you’re young.

And an article at the A.V. CLub gives a good interpretation on the meanings:

So what is “Tom Courtenay” about—or, rather, who? Mainly it’s about the person singing it: Not Kaplan per se, but the character he’s playing in the song. Judging by the references to “the needle,” the lyrics are being sung by some junkie in a darkened room, obsessed with Billy Liar and actress Eleanor Bron’s performance in The Beatles movie Help! While the guitar feedback and the chorus of “ba ba ba”s billows outward, “Tom Courtenay” finds a potent mix of upbeat and bittersweet. It alludes to showbiz nostalgia while suggesting other, darker compulsions.

songs.full_title: Paul Is Dead by Yo La Tengo
songs.title: Paul Is Dead

description.plain:
This nifty little song from Yo La Tengo’s classic album Electr-O-Pura has somewhat straightforward lyrics about banal and not so banal events – observing a stranger on the street, meeting someone in a random situation and begining a relationship from there.



The title is an obvious reference to the old conspiracy theory that claim that Paul McCartney died in 1966 and was replaced by a lookalike.
It seems not to be in any way related to the lyrics. Perhaps the band was making a joke about fans trying to find hidden meaning where there isn’t. Also ironic that not the Beatles, but The Rolling Stones are mentioned in the song. Paul appeared in another song from the same album, however.

It seems not to be in any way related to the lyrics. Perhaps the band was making a joke about fans trying to find hidden meaning where there isn’t. Also ironic that not the Beatles, but The Rolling Stones are mentioned in the song. Paul appeared in another song from the same album, however.
